TITLE: Edge Cases of Backreference Syntax in JavaScript RegExp
DESCRIPTION: This code block demonstrates additional edge cases where backreference-like syntax is not actually creating useless backreferences. In these cases, the syntax is interpreted differently, such as octal escape sequences when a referenced group doesn't exist.
SOURCE: https://github.com/eslint/eslint/blob/main/docs/src/rules/no-useless-backreference.md#2025-04-14_snippet_3

LANGUAGE: javascript
CODE:
```
/*eslint no-useless-backreference: "error"*/

// comments describe behavior in a browser

/^[\1](a)$/.test("\x01a"); // true. In a character class, \1 is treated as an octal escape sequence.
/^\1$/.test("\x01"); // true. Since the group 1 doesn't exist, \1 is treated as an octal escape sequence.
/^(a)\1\2$/.test("aa\x02"); // true. In this case, \1 is a backreference, \2 is an octal escape sequence.
```

